# Convert a Image File to a Base64 string and reverse

## Why converting a image file to a Base64 string ?
In PowerShell, encoding an image in Base64 may be necessary for several reasons:

 - Data Transfer: Base64 encoding is used when we want to transfer data, especially binary data like an image, over a network in an ASCII string format so that the data remains intact during transport.
- Integration into other documents: Preliminary processing of the Image format is necessary so that the data remains intact without modification during transport or integration into other documents (HTML, XML, JSON or CSS).
- Speed up loading time: Base64 encoding images can speed up the loading time of smaller images and icons by avoiding additional requests.

## Convert Image File to Base64

````powershell
# first encoding the Image File to Byte
$ImageByte = Get-Content -Path "C:\Users\Olivier\OneDrive\Images\Always DNS.jpg" -Encoding Byte
````
The output is like the following
````output
...

````

In a second step, we are using the `[System.Convert]` class and its method `Tobase64String()` to convert the bytes to Base64String

````powershell
$Base64StringImage=[System.Convert]::ToBase64String($imageByte)
````
The output looks like the following
````Output

````

Now, we can use this Base64 string in our Powershell code. No need to have an additional file. 

### Shorter way

````Powershell
$Base64StringImage=[Convert]::ToBase64String(Get-Content -Path "C:\Users\Olivier\OneDrive\Images\Always DNS.jpg" -Encoding Byte)
````

>[Nota] : `[Convert]` is formally the `[System.Convert]` class.


## Convert a Base64 String to a Image file


````Powershell 
# Convert Base64 string to byte string
$Base64ToString = [System.Convert]::FromBase64String($Base64StringImage)
# convert this byte string to a Stream
$Stream = [System.IO.MemoryStream]::new($Base64ToString) # or [System.IO.MemoryStream]$Base64ToString
<#

# Convert this stream to Bitmap
$Image = [System.Drawing.Bitmap]::FromStream($Stream)
<#

# And finally save it
$Image.Save("c:\temp\ImageAlwaysDNS.jpg")
````

### Shorter way

````powershell
$Image = [Drawing.Bitmap]::FromStream([IO.MemoryStream][Convert]::FromBase64String($Base64StringImage))
$Image.Save("c:\temp\ImageAlwaysDNS.jpg")
````

>[Nota 1] : `[Drawing.Bitmap]` is formally the `[System.Drawing.Bitmap]` class.

>[Nota 2] : With PS version 5.1 with VSCode, the assemblies `[System]`, `[System.Drawing]` are not loaded. In this case, you could use first : 
> 
> `[Reflection.Assembly]::LoadWithPartialName("System")`
> ````Output
> [Reflection.Assembly]::LoadWithPartialName("System")
>
> GAC    Version        Location
> ---    -------        --------
> True   v4.0.30319     C:\WINDOWS\Microsoft.Net\assembly\GAC_MSIL\System\v4.0_4.0.0.0__b77a5c561934e089\System.dll
> ````
> This load the Assembly `System`
> And use 
> `[Reflection.Assembly]::LoadWithPartialName("System.Drawing")`
> ````output
> [Reflection.Assembly]::LoadWithPartialName("System.Drawing")       
>
> GAC    Version        Location
> ---    -------        --------
> True   v4.0.30319     C:\WINDOWS\Microsoft.Net\assembly\GAC_MSIL\System.Drawing\v4.0_4.0.0.0__b03f5f7f11d50a3a\System.Drawing.dll````
> 
> to load other necessary assembly.

````powershell
[Reflection.Assembly]::LoadWithPartialName("System")
[Reflection.Assembly]::LoadWithPartialName("System.Drawing")
$Image = [Drawing.Bitmap]::FromStream([IO.MemoryStream][Convert]::FromBase64String($Base64StringImage))
$Image.Save("c:\temp\ImageAlwaysDNS.jpg")
````
